#  Multicollinearity has several effects, these are described as follow :
#- High variance of coefficients may reduce the precision of estimation.
#- Multicollinearity can result in coefficients appearing to have the wrong sign.
#- Estimates of coefficients may be sensitive to particular sets of sample data.
#- Some variables may be dropped from the model although, they are important in the population.
#- The coefficients are sensitive of to the presence of small number inaccurate data values
approaches = '(1)using a latent variable to eliminate spurious relationship (2)combining the relative variables into one variable. (3)removing one of the relative variables (4)using other regressions, like PCA regression, PLS regression'

#IV.a

breakevenrate = (10/1000) / (0.05*25)
tz.test1 <- myprediction %>%
  filter(training == 'test')%>%
  mutate(Pred.click=if_else(click_logit > breakevenrate,'pred.yes','pred.no'))%>%
  select(click, click_logit, Pred.click)
acc <- function(mat,question){
  qeustion <- (mat[1,2]+mat[2,1])/sum(mat)
  cat('Model Accuracy=', qeustion)
}
conf.mat1 <- table(tz.test1$click,tz.test1$Pred.click)

#V.a

cost = 10/1000
breakevenrate = cost / marginonsale

#V.b

profit.analysis <- myprediction %>%
  mutate(target_logit=if_else(click_logit > breakevenrate,'TRUE','FALSE'))

#V.c

perf_calc <- function(df,model){
  df %>%
  filter(colum == 'TRUE') %>%
  mutate(costs = cost*impup, profit = marginonsale- cost*costs)%>%
  summarize(Profit = sum(profit), Costs=sum(costs))
  Profits = df$Profit - costimpressions
  ROME = Profits/(df$Costs + costimpressions)
  print(paste0(df, ' profit is: ', Profits,2))
  print(paste0(df, ' ROME is: ', ROME,' %'))
  return(data.frame(Profits, ROME))
}

perf_calc <- function(df,model){
  result1 = df %>%
  filter(training == 'test')%>%
  mutate(target_logit =if_else(click_logit > breakevenrate,'TRUE','FALSE'))%>%
  filter(target_logit == 'TRUE') %>%
  mutate(costs = cost*impup, profit = marginonsale- cost*costs)%>%
  summarize(Profit = sum(profit), Costs=sum(costs))
  Profit.test = result1$Profit
  ROME.test = result1$Profit/result1$Costs
  data.test = data.frame(Profit.test, ROME.test)
  print(paste0(model, ' profit is: ', round(Profit.test,2)))
  print(paste0(model, ' ROME is: ', round(ROME.test*100,2),' %'))
  
  result2 = df %>%
  mutate(target_logit =if_else(click_logit > breakevenrate,'TRUE','FALSE'))%>%
  summarize(rate = mean(target_logit == 'TRUE'))
  if (model == 'model2'){
    extra = 0
  }else if (model == 'model5'){
    extra = 150000
  }else{
    extra = 50000
  }
  Profit.all = size*(result2$rate*marginonsale - cost)- extra
  ROME.all = Profit.all/(costimpressions+extra)
  data.all = data.frame(Profit.all, ROME.all)
  print(paste0(model, ' all profit is: ', round(Profit.all,2)))
  print(paste0(model, ' all ROME is: ', round(ROME.all*100,2),' %'))
  
  return(result2)
}
